<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-006-118 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 559 646</DOCID><JOURNAL>Los Angeles Times  Nov 28 1991 v110 pD1 21 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM should use Japan's formula. (organizational structure andmanagement) (Innovation) (Company Profile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schrage, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM, which is planning an extensive restructuring anddecentralization, should consider Japanese models of organization.andO;The Japanese zaibatsu and keiretsu were originally created in theMeiji era as organizational devices suited to importing advancedtechnology into Japan.andP;  These Japanese inventions are still wellsuited to high-technology industries, which are characterized byshort life cycles with high Randamp;D costs.andP;  Instead of setting upvarious semi-independent businesses oriented upward toward acontrolling entity, IBM should emphasize horizontal and diagonalconnectivity as the zaibatsu and keiritsu do.andP;  There is no doubtthat IBM needs to be restructured.andP;  The question is how to bestaccomplish reorganization.andP;  Japanese zaibatsu and keiritsu couldprovide an effective and flexible model.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Organization StructureJapanReorganizationBureaucracyDecentralization.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>